Let's first recall that a company can acquire another paying with cash or stocks. When this transaction is made by exchanging stocks, the number of shares outstanding in the new firm (after acquisition) is determined by the sum of the shares of the bidding company and the shares offered to the acquired firm`s shareholders during the acquisition. 
Let's take a look at the following formula: 

$${
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Shares outstanding}\\
\text{after acquisition}
\end{array}
= 
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Shares of Harrods}\\
\text{PLC before acquisition} 
\end{array}
+ 
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Shares offered}\\ 
\text{to Selfridge shareholders} 
\end{array}
\end{equation}
}
$$

Due to the change for shares outstanding, the stock price after the acquisition is also modified. To know the new share price we divide the value of the new firm (combined) with synergy by the number of shares outstanding after acquisition and the following formula can express this:

$$
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\text{New stock price}\\ 
\text{of Harrods}\\
\text{after acquisition}
\end{array} 
= 
\frac{
\text{Value of combined firm with synergy}}{\text{Shares outstanding after acquisition}}      
\end{equation}

$$

First, we need to calculate the **amount of shares outstanding** after acquisition using the formula $(1)$:

$$
\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Shares outstanding}\\ 
\text{after acquisition}
\end{array}
 &= 4.5 \text{ million shares } + 1.1 \text{ million shares}\\
 &= 5.6 \text{ million shares } 
\end{align*}
$$
The amount of shares outstanding in the new firm after the acquisition is $5.6$ million shares.

Now let's substitute the shares outstanding after acquisition in formula 2 to calculate the new stock price!

$$
\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{c}
\text{New stock price of Harrods}\\
\text{after acquisition}
\end{array}
&=
 \frac{\text{Value of combined firm with synergy}}{ \text{Shares outstanding after acquisition}}\\[10pt]
&= \frac{£145 \text{ million}}{5.6 \text{ million shares}}\\[10pt]
&= \pounds 25.89 
\end{align*}
$$

***<span style="color: #4257B2">The stock price of Harrods after the acquisition would be $\bold{\pounds 25.89}$ per share</span>***.

First, let`s recall ***what is the exchange ratio?***

The **exchange ratio** only exists in deals that are paid for in stock or a mix of stock and cash as opposed to just cash. It expresses how many shares an acquiring company needs to issue for each share an investor owns in a target company to provide its relative value. 

The calculation for the **exchange ratio** can be made by dividing the **target share price** by the **acquirer share price**:

$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Exchange ratio} = \frac{\text{Target share price}}{\text{Acquirer share price}}
\end{equation}
$$

Then, let's see what is the value of the offer by multiplying the amount of shares Harrods offered to Selfridge by its price before the acquisition. 
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Value of the offer} &= 1.1 \text{ million shares}\times \pounds 21.1 \text{ per share} \\
&=\pounds 23.2 \text{ million} 
\end{align*}
$$

So this stock offer is equivalent to a cash offer of $\pounds 23.2$ million. 

Let's calculate the **Exchange ratio** for this reference offer: 
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Exchange ratio} &= \frac{\text{Target share price}}{\text{Acquirer share price}}\\[10pt]
&= \frac{\pounds 17.7}{\pounds 21.1}\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{0.84}
\end{align*}
$$
The result is $0.84$. This means Harrods has to issue $0.84$ of its own shares for every $1$ share of Selfridge (the Target it plans to acquire). 

This is the **exchange ratio** when the stock offer is equivalent to a cash offer of $\pounds 23.2$ million.

## Step 2: Calculate the stock price for a new offer equivalent to the cash offer of £35.3 million. 

The offer equivalent to $\pounds 35.3$ million would cover Selfridge's Market value and the Takeover premium. Let's see why:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Stock offer} &= \text{Market value} + \text{Takeover Premium}\\[10pt]
\pounds 35.3 \text{ million} &= 1.8 \text{ million shares} \times \pounds 17.7 \text{ per share} + \pounds 3.3 \text{ million}
\end{align*}
$$

Now, if the offer is $\pounds 35.3$ million we can recalculate the stock price for Selfridge:
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Stock price}_{\text{ Selfridge}} &=\frac{ \pounds 35.3\text{ million}}{1.8 \text{ million}}\\[10pt]
&= \pounds 19.6 \text{ per share}
\end{align*}
$$
Considering the new value per stock, we recalculate the exchange ratio. Is logical to suppose the amount of stocks would vary if their value changes:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Exchange ratio} &=\frac{\text{Target share price}}{\text{Acquirer share price}}\\[10pt]
&=\frac{\pounds 19.6}{\pounds 21.1}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{ 0.93}
\end{align*}
$$
The result is $0.93$. This means Harrods has to issue $0.93$ of its own shares for every $1$ share of Selfridge (the Target it plans to acquire). This is the **exchange ratio** when the stock offer is equivalent to a cash offer of $\pounds 35.3$ million.
